title: For Sale:  1969 Ishapore 2A1 7.62x51 Indian Lee Enfield No1 MKIII ALL Matching
postcontent:
I had this professionally restored.  I never fired it.  Bore is shiny/strong rifling.  12rd detachable magazine. Bolt, stock, receiver, magazine, rear sight and barrel match.  Everything with numbers. I have more pics on request. The Rifle 7.62mm 2A/2A1 (also known as the Ishapore 2A/2A1) is a 7.62mm NATO (7.62×51) calibre bolt-action rifle adopted as a reserve arm by the Indian Armed Forces in 1963. The design of the rifle - initially the Rifle 7.62mm 2A - began at the Ishapore Rifle Factory of the Ordnance Factories Board in India, soon after the Sino-Indian War of 1962.
The Ishapore 2A/2A1 has the distinction of being the last bolt-action rifle designed to be used by a regular military force other than specialized sniper rifles. The Ishapore 2A and 2A1 rifles are often incorrectly described as ".308 conversions". In fact, the 2A/2A1 rifles are not conversions of .303 calibre SMLE Mk III* rifles: they were designed and built right from the outset to fire 7.62mm NATO ammunition.
Due to fluctuating supplies of affordable .303 British ammunition, the Ishapore rifles are becoming increasingly popular with civilian shooters and collectors in Australia, United Kingdom and the United States.
Externally the Ishapore 2A/2A1 rifle was based upon (and is almost identical to) the .303 British calibre SMLE Mk III* rifle, with the exception of the distinctive “square” (10 or 12 round) magazine. The rifle was designed to allow the British Pattern 1907 (P'07) sword bayonet to be attached. There were other differences to the Ishapore 2A/2A1 rifles that include the use of improved steel (to handle the increased pressures of the 7.62mm NATO round), and a redesigned extractor to cope with the rimless round. Production of these rifles started in early 1960s and is believed to have been discontinued in 1975. The original (2A) design incorporated the Lee-Enfield rear sight which had metric graduations out to 2000 meters. The re-designated "Rifle 7.62mm 2A1" incorporated a more realistic 800 meter rear sight. The stock is recycled from the No. 1 Mk. III armory stock, with the addition of a cross screw forward of the magazine well.
Price includes shipping to FFL....

title: For Sale:  Modern (1967) Iver Johnson Viking .38 Revolver
location: Santa Fe, NM, New Mexico, United States
postcontent:
OK, this has to be one of the ugliest revolvers in modern times. BUT - it is great shape, shoots well, and is fairly unusual nowadays. LOL, I know what you are thinking. It's unusual for a reason. WUHG. World Ugliest Handgun!!! SO ugly you will brag to your friends and show it off like I did! This is the Shar-Pei of handguns. Especially to you young guys who are used to Glocks. You must be thinking I am crzay right about now. 

Nope.

This Iver Johnosn is a bit unique in that it is a topbreak, as well as a hand ejector. The rear sight boss is also the catch to open the revolver so it breaks open like a shotgun. Then you eject the emptys with that rod that is under the barrel.  It has a modern sight picture, and the previous owner put a dab of bright orange paint on the rear face of the front sight. I just left it on because it is quite visible, but it will just wipe off if you want it gone. Condition is about 99% to new and it even has some nice swirly factory plastic grips. They are indeed factory, believe it or not. 

All kidding aside (if that is possible with this revolver) it is actually quite well made. I looked it up when I got it, and it was apparently made in 1967 before Iver Johnson fell on hard times. The Iver Johnson Arms and Cycle Works (yep, that was their name) was at one time the largest gunmaker in the US, but they kept making handguns like this long after they were out of style. I originally bought this revolver to keep in my truck, but it turned out to be just too nice for that. I recently sold my collection of Iver Johnson antiques, so it no longer fits my collecting needs.

This is chambered in .38 S&W, not .38 Special. I have a few rounds on hand that will go with it. Last time I was in Ron Peterson's they had boxes and boxes of that ammo, but no .38 Special. So in a way this is a good thing. The .38 S&W uses a bullet that is slightly larger in diameter than a .38 Special in case you didn't know. It is a true .38 where the .38 Special shoots a .357 bullet. Confusing, yes. The .38 S&W came before the .38 S&W Special though. It was the British Commonwealth service ammunition during and until well after WWII, and is effective while easy to control. The two rounds are not interchangeable obviously. 

At any rate, I actually like the way it looks and shoots, and it is probably a future collectible if it isn't already. I have been around guns a LOT for the past 45 years, and this is the only one  in a large caliberI have ever seen, let alone owned. I think you will like it. I have shot 27 rounds through it, and when I got it, it was unfired. So if you want to take a trip back to the 1960s this handgun will do it. It isn't a Glock, but it will never jam, and when something goes wrong in the night it will always shoot. I joke about the looks, but the finish and fit on this gun is way above what most guns can offer nowadays. 

Best of all this is a real handgun in a serious caliber for not much money. 

Thanks for reading my long winded ad. If you want to see it, contact me through Armslist with your phone number and I will call you to arrange to meet. If you are out of reach to drive to Santa Fe, this is a modern handgun, so I would have to ship it to an FFL. Shipping on handguns usually runs around $35-$40 since they have to go overnight.

If you like unusual but practicall guns, bring your money when you come up because I think you will like this one. 

Doby

title: For Trade:  1934 m91/30 mosin nagant
postcontent:
Nagants in good enough shape to be salvaged were part of the soviets massive refurbishment program following ww2. The primary reasons behind the huge post war overhaul of large, obsolete rifle stockpiles were the anticipation of another impending world war, and the plan to call up seasoned veterans in defense of the motherland. Already familiar with their old mosin nagant rifles and revolvers, those veterans would likely have required very little new training and would easily and rapidly reintegrate into the red machine. 
 With the development of newer semi auots that would have required extensive massive retraining, the important issue became of quick mobilization became apearant. However time passed and those great ww2 veterans eventually aged beyond the point of viability.  While newer weapons took over the worlds battlefields, the stocks of long outdated ordnance were now imported to the USA. 

This is a pre war 1934 izzy manufacture m90/31 with hexagonal reciever with original russian laminate non refurbished stock. This rifles bore is stone mint shiny chromed out! "Have neer seen one like this"  the weapon bears No refurbishment marks or other countrys arsenal  markings! The metal has not a mark on it is stone mint! The magazine follower, action etc have no wear! Mint bore. All matching. No refurbishment marks from other countrys !!
 This is a very early import that was sold wrapped in brown paper tied in twine.  This rifle saw little to no action its entire life, maybe an officers or political gaurds weapon

The rifles antiquated lines, and historical signifigance is something to be sought after for years to come. This rifle was made well when an individuals workmanship was apreciated and one took pride in what they did. It also was a matter of national pride, a "we made it here" battle rifle.
